To solve this, we first note the key property of the matrix identity, and then we use Python to compute the final answer.</think><answer>

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{A} + \mathbf{B} &= \mathbf{A} \mathbf{B} \\
\mathbf{B} &= \mathbf{A} \mathbf{B} - \mathbf{A} \\
&= \mathbf{A}(\mathbf{B} - \mathbf{I}) \quad \text{(1)}
\end{align*}

On the other hand, we have
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{A} \mathbf{B} &= \begin{pmatrix} 20/3 & 4/3 \\ -8/3 & 8/3 \end{pmatrix} \\
\mathbf{A} \mathbf{B} - \mathbf{I} &= \begin{pmatrix} 17/3 & 4/3 \\ -8/3 & 5/3 \end{pmatrix} \\
\mathbf{A}(\mathbf{B} - \mathbf{I}) &= \mathbf{A} \mathbf{B} - \mathbf{A} \\
\mathbf{A} - \mathbf{B} &= \begin{pmatrix} 17/3 & 4/3 \\ -8/3 & 5/3 \end{pmatrix} \\
\mathbf{B} &= \mathbf{A} - \begin{pmatrix} 17/3 & 4/3 \\ -8/3 & 5/3 \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} 1/3 & -4/3 \\ 8/3 & 3 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

From (1), we have $\mathbf{B} = \mathbf{A}(\mathbf{B} - \mathbf{I})$. We can use this to find $\mathbf{B} \mathbf{A}$:

\[\mathbf{B} \mathbf{A} = \mathbf{A}(\mathbf{B} - \mathbf{I}) \mathbf{A} = \begin{pmatrix} 1/3 & -4/3 \\ 8/3 & 3 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} -4/3 & 1/3 \\ 8/3 & 3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 20 \end{pmatrix}.\]

Hence, the answer is $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 20 \end{pmatrix}}$.</answer>

problem:
Rhombus $ABCD$ is similar to rhombus $BFDE$. The area of rhombus $ABCD$ is 24, and $\angle BAD=60^\circ$. What is the area of rhombus $BFDE$?

[asy]
pair A,B,C,D,I,F;
A=(0,0);
B=(10,0);
C=(15,8.7);
D=(5,8.7);
I=(5,2.88);
F=(10,5.82);
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
draw(D--I--B--F--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
label("$A$",A,SW);
label("$B$",B,SE);
label("$C$",C,NE);
label("$D$",D,NW);
label("$E$",I,W);
label("$F$",F,E);
[/asy]

solution:
Since $\angle BAD = 60^{\circ}$, isosceles $\triangle
BAD$ is also equilateral. As a consequence, $\triangle AEB$, $\triangle AED$, $\triangle BED$, $\triangle BFD$, $\triangle
BFC$, and $\triangle CFD$ are congruent. These six triangles have equal areas and their union forms  rhombus $ABCD$, so each has area $24/6 = 4$. Rhombus $BFDE$ is the union of  $\triangle BED$ and $\triangle BFD$, so its area is $\boxed{8}.$

[asy]
pair A,B,C,D,I,F;
A=(0,0);
B=(10,0);
C=(15,8.7);
D=(5,8.7);
I=(5,2.88);
F=(10,5.82);
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
draw(D--I--B--F--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
label("$A$",A,SW);
label("$B$",B,SE);
label("$C$",C,NE);
label("$D$",D,NW);
label("$E$",I,NW);
label("$F$",F,E);
draw(A--I,linewidth(0.7));
draw(F--C,linewidth(0.7));
draw(D--B,linewidth(0.7));
[/asy]

